title: For Sale:  (SALE PENDING) WW2 Japanese Arisaka Type 38 Carbine
postcontent: ON HOLD FOR PENDING SALEThis Arisaka Type 38 Carbine in 6.5x50mm Japanese caliber was used by Japanese troops early in WW2 along side the Type 38 long rifle, and eventually it's successor, the Type 99 rifle.  It was manufactured at the Koishikawa (Tokyo) arsenal.  While the exact date of manufacture is unknown since the production records were destroyed in the war, it was inspected by a friend who is a nationally published author and recognized expert on Japanese long guns and he felt that it was probably made some time around 1934.  He also noted that rifle had seen a good amount of front line service and had "been there, done that".  It's a fine example of a WW2 Japanese main battle rifle and would make a great addition to a WW2 firearms collection.The mum is ground and while the receiver and bolt serial numbers do not match, the bolt and bolt stop number do match, which may indicate that the carbine may be an "assembly numbers" match.  I'd call the bore VG, and while I've never fired it, it will probably be a good shooter.  It includes the (frequently missing) cleaning rod and a VERY good reproduction of an extremely rare "quick disconnect" sling which was sometimes found on early Type 38's and carbines.The price is $380 face-to-face in Jacksonville, FL.  Buyer must be at least 18 years of age, must be a Florida resident, have a valid Florida driver license or Concealed Weapons Permit, or a C&R license.  I will provide a bill of sale.
